   science:"mRNA <span class='hl'>cannot enter the cell nucleus where DNA is stored</span>. It's read by ribosomes in the cytoplasm, makes the spike protein, then is broken down within hours to days. Your cells destroy mRNA constantly — it's how normal biology works. You'd need reverse transcriptase (which human cells don't have active) to even theoretically convert mRNA to DNA.",
   evidence:"CDC; Nature Reviews Immunology, 2021; basic molecular biology (Central Dogma)",
